{"title_page": "A1 (Newcastle upon Tyne)", "text_new": "The '''[[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1 road]]''' around [[Gateshead]] and [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] after arriving from the south as the [[A1(M)]] from its origin in [[London]], currently runs from the A1(M) terminus at [[Birtley, Tyne and Wear|Birtley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A1|title=A1 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref> It then swings to the west of both Gateshead and Newcastle via Coal House, [[Lobley Hill]], [[MetroCentre (shopping centre)|Metrocentre]], [[Swalwell]], [[Blaydon Bridge]], [[West Denton]], [[Fawdon]] and [[Wideopen]] to [[Seaton Burn]] interchange before continuing north towards [[Edinburgh]].\n\nHowever, the A1 has followed a number of different routes in the Newcastle area, matching road developments aimed at reducing traffic congestion.\n\n== Historic routes ==\n[[File:A1innewcastle.jpg|thumb|right|450px|Historical routes of the A1 road and motorway in and around the Newcastle upon Tyne area.]]\n'''Pre-1977'''\n\nThe [[Great North Road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]] and later the first incarnation of the A1 passed directly through [[Low Fell]], [[Gateshead]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Gosforth]] and [[Wideopen]] before rejoining the current A1 at [[Seaton Burn]].   The Great North Road was effectively diverted from the [[Swing Bridge]] to the [[Tyne Bridge]] when it opened on 25 February 1928, the A1 passing up [[Pilgrim Street]] and [[Northumberland Street]].   The later first incarnation of Newcastle's Central Motorway built during the 1970s and passing just to the east of Newcastle City Centre, was initially numbered A1(M).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a1m_central_motorway_east/|title=Pathetic Motorways|first=Steven|last=Jukes|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe portion of Great North Road through Gateshead and Newcastle has had a number of designations since it ceased being the A1 in 1977. Between 1977 and 1993, it was numbered A6127 between Birtley and Newcastle (the Newcastle Central Motorway being renumbered A6127(M) at this time) and A6125 between Newcastle and Seaton Burn\u2014both road numbers are now redundant.<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A6127|title=A6127 - Roader\u2032s Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a6127m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|first=Steven|last=Jukes|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A6125|title=A6125 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref>   Since 1993, the Birtley to Newcastle section has formed part of the [[A167]] (the Central Motorway being renumbered A167(M)) and the Newcastle to Seaton Burn A6125 section has been the B1318.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/current/a167m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|first=Steven|last=Jukes|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=B1318|title=B1318 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n'''1977 to 1993'''\n\nAfter the opening of the [[Tyne Tunnel]] on 19 October 1967, the main route for traffic around Gateshead and Newcastle was diverted to the east.<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A19|title=A19 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref> With completion of the A1(M) through [[County Durham]] in the 1970s, from 1977 onward the A1 ran as the A1(M) from Birtley past the north of [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]] to the Newcastle Road / Leam Lane junction near [[Wardley, Gateshead|Wardley]] (this section is now numbered [[A194(M) motorway|A194(M)]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A1/via_Tyne_Tunnel|title=A1/via Tyne Tunnel - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A194|title=A194 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref> It then ran east to Testo's Roundabout near [[West Boldon]], following what is now a section of the [[A184 road (England)|A184]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A184|title=A184 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref> At Testos Roundabout, the A1 turned north following what is now the northern section of the [[A19 road|A19]] towards [[Jarrow]] and the [[Tyne Tunnel]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk1\"/>\n\nNorth of the Tyne Tunnel, the A1 passed through [[Howdon]], before it continued in a north-westerly direction, through North Tyneside past [[Killingworth]] and [[Cramlington]], rejoining the current A1, just north of Newcastle at Seaton Burn. Again, this section of road has been redesignated [[A19 road|A19]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk1\"/>\n\nThe section of road now forming the A19 between Testo's Roundabout and Seaton Burn was numbered the A108 (encompassing also the A19 Sunderland bypass) prior to it being numbered the A1 then A19 as detailed above.<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk1\"/>\n\n'''1993 onwards'''\n\nThe [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] officially assumed its western route in 1993, with completion of the Newcastle Western Bypass and opening of the [[Blaydon Bridge]] on 3 December 1990. The Gateshead Western Bypass, forming the southern part of this western route, was renumbered from [[A69 road (England)|A69]] to its current A1 number.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A69|title=A69 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Related changes to the A1 in Yorkshire and County Durham ==\n\nHistorically, the A1 followed its current route to just north of [[Boroughbridge]], then following the route of the current [[A168]] at [[Dishforth]] to [[Topcliffe, North Yorkshire|Topcliffe]] (south west of [[Thirsk]].   It then followed the route of the current [[A167]], crossing the [[A61 road (England)|A61]] near [[Carlton Miniott]], then continuing as the A167 via [[Kirby Wiske]], [[Northallerton]], [[Great Smeaton]], [[Dalton-on-Tees]] to the border between [[North Yorkshire]] and [[County Durham]], crossing the [[River Tees|Tees]] at [[Croft-on-Tees]].<ref name=\"A167 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE W\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A167|title=A167 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nBeyond Croft-on-Tees, the original A1 continued to follow the current route of the A167 through [[Darlington]], [[Durham, England|Durham]], [[Chester-le-Street]] before reaching [[Birtley, Tyne and Wear|Birtley]].  Until 1993, the Chester-le-Street to Birtley section was the southern portion of the A6127 before being renumbered A167.<ref name=\"A167 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE W\"/>\n\nThis section is now bypassed by the [[A1(M)]] from [[Dishforth]] to [[Birtley, Tyne and Wear|Birtley]]. The Dishforth to [[Barton, North Yorkshire|Barton]] section was dual carriageway trunk road numbered A1 until the Dishforth to [[Leeming, North Yorkshire|Leeming]] section was upgraded to motorway in 2012, with the Leeming to Barton upgrade finally being completed in 2018.<ref>https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A1(M)/Darrington_-_Birtley</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1-0001}}\n[[Category:Roads in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Motorways in England]]\n", "text_old": "The '''[[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1 road]]''' around [[Gateshead]] and [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] after arriving from the south as the [[A1(M)]] from its origin in [[London]], currently runs from the A1(M) terminus at [[Birtley, Tyne and Wear|Birtley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A1|title=A1 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref> It then swings to the west of both Gateshead and Newcastle via Coal House, [[Lobley Hill]], [[MetroCentre (shopping centre)|Metrocentre]], [[Swalwell]], [[Blaydon Bridge]], [[West Denton]], [[Fawdon]] and [[Wideopen]] to [[Seaton Burn]] interchange before continuing north towards [[Edinburgh]].\n\nHowever, the A1 has followed a number of different routes in the Newcastle area, matching road developments aimed at reducing traffic congestion.\n\n== Historic routes ==\n[[File:A1innewcastle.jpg|thumb|right|450px|Historical routes of the A1 road and motorway in and around the Newcastle upon Tyne area.]]\n'''Pre-1977'''\n\nThe [[Great North Road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]] and later the first incarnation of the A1 passed directly through [[Low Fell]], [[Gateshead]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Gosforth]] and [[Wideopen]] before rejoining the current A1 at [[Seaton Burn]].   The Great North Road was effectively diverted from the [[Swing Bridge]] to the [[Tyne Bridge]] when it opened on 25 February 1928, the A1 passing up [[Pilgrim Street]] and [[Northumberland Street]].   The later first incarnation of Newcastle's Central Motorway built during the 1970s and passing just to the east of Newcastle City Centre, was initially numbered A1(M).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a1m_central_motorway_east/|title=Pathetic Motorways|first=Steven|last=Jukes|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe portion of Great North Road through Gateshead and Newcastle has had a number of designations since it ceased being the A1 in 1977. Between 1977 and 1993, it was numbered A6127 between Birtley and Newcastle (the Newcastle Central Motorway being renumbered A6127(M) at this time) and A6125 between Newcastle and Seaton Burn\u2014both road numbers are now redundant.<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A6127|title=A6127 - Roader\u2032s Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a6127m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|first=Steven|last=Jukes|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A6125|title=A6125 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref>   Since 1993, the Birtley to Newcastle section has formed part of the [[A167]] (the Central Motorway being renumbered A167(M)) and the Newcastle to Seaton Burn A6125 section has been the B1318.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/current/a167m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|first=Steven|last=Jukes|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=B1318|title=B1318 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n'''1977 to 1993'''\n\nAfter the opening of the [[Tyne Tunnel]] on 19 October 1967, the main route for traffic around Gateshead and Newcastle was diverted to the east.<ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A19|title=A19 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref> With completion of the A1(M) through [[County Durham]] in the 1970s, from 1977 onward the A1 ran as the A1(M) from Birtley past the north of [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]] to the Newcastle Road / Leam Lane junction near [[Wardley, Gateshead|Wardley]] (this section is now numbered [[A194(M) motorway|A194(M)]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A1/via_Tyne_Tunnel|title=A1/via Tyne Tunnel - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"sabre-roads.org.uk2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A194|title=A194 - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk}}</r